#{{note|ICC membership}} See the [https://web.archive.org/web/20060220172457/http://www.icc-cricket.com/about/history.html International Cricket Council] for the dates by year on which teams became full members. For the precise dates, see CricketArchive as follows: [https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Countries/30.html West Indies], [https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Countries/21.html New Zealand], [https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Countries/14.html India].
#{{note|Test designation}} Which matches have been recognised as Test matches up to 1909, when the Imperial Cricket Conference, now the International Cricket Council, was formed, have been long-established through custom. After 1909, Test matches have been official matches between full members of the ICC. The exception to this is that matches played between South Africa and full members after South Africa left the [[Commonwealth of Nations|Commonwealth]] in 1961 and the 1970–71 South African season are recognised as Tests, and the ICC recognised a match between Australia and a World XI that took place in 2005 as an official Test.
#{{note|First series}} See [https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Seasons/ENG/1928_ENG_West_Indies_in_England_1928.html CricketArchive] and [http://www.cricinfo.com/link_to_database/ARCHIVE/1920S/1928/WI_IN_ENG/ Cricinfo] for first-class scorecards.
#{{note|1930–31 picture}} Source [[Don Bradman]] scrapbooks, vol. 11, 1930/31, p.&nbsp;35. Summary A photograph of the West Indies Cricket Team which toured Australia in 1930/31. The photograph includes the players and the Manager and Assistant Manager.
#{{note|1929–30 tour}} See [https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Seasons/WI/1929-30_WI_Marylebone_Cricket_Club_in_West_Indies_1929-30.html CricketArchive] and [http://www.cricinfo.com/link_to_database/ARCHIVE/1920S/1929-30/ENG_IN_WI/ Cricinfo] for the first-class scorecards.
#{{note|1930–31 tour}} See [https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Seasons/AUS/1930-31_AUS_West_Indies_in_Australia_1930-31.html CricketArchive] and [http://www.cricinfo.com/link_to_database/ARCHIVE/1930S/1930-31/WI_IN_AUS/ Cricinfo] for the first-class scorecards.
#{{note|White Australia}} For an analysis of the effects of the [[White Australia]] policy on cricket, including an account of this tour, see ''A History of Australian Cricket'' by Chris Harte with Bernard Whimpress {{ISBN|0-233-05130-9}} .
#{{note|Bodyline tour}} The England's "[[Bodyline]]" tour of Australia in 1932–33 was one of the most politically charged tours of all time. See [https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Seasons/AUS/1932-33_AUS_Marylebone_Cricket_Club_in_Australia_1932-33.html CricketArchive] and [http://www.cricinfo.com/db/NATIONAL/ENG/SERIES/ALL.html Cricinfo] for the scorecards, and ''[[Bodyline]]'' for detailed information.
#{{note|Bodyline by WI}} See, for example, [[Alan Gibson]] (1988). ''The Cricket Captains of England''. The Pavilion Library. {{ISBN|1-85145-395-4}}.
#{{note|Bodyline scorecard}} For the scorecard of the game in which Constantine and Martindale bowled Bodyline at England, see [https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/14/14750.html CricketArchive] or [http://www.cricinfo.com/link_to_database/ARCHIVE/1930S/1933/WI_IN_ENG/WI_ENG_T2_22-25JUL1933.html Cricinfo]
#{{note|Constantine picture}} Source: State Library of New South Wales (http://image.sl.nsw.gov.au/cgi-bin/ebindshow.pl?doc=pxe789_42/a372;seq=23). For more on Constantine, see, for example, [https://web.archive.org/web/20041204234858/http://www.nalis.gov.tt/Biography/EMANCIPATORS_LearieConstantine.html ''The Emancipators: Learie Constantine''] from the ''Trinidad Guardian''
#{{note|1934–35 tour}} See [https://web.archive.org/web/20090618143535/http://www.cricketarchive.com/Archive/Seasons/WI/1934-35_WI_Marylebone_Cricket_Club_in_West_Indies_1934-35.html CricketArchive] and [http://www.cricinfo.com/link_to_database/ARCHIVE/1930S/1934-35/ENG_IN_WI/ Cricinfo] for the first-class scorecards. A brief report of the extraordinary events in the First Test is available on [http://www.cricinfo.com/link_to_database/ARCHIVE/1930S/1934-35/ENG_IN_WI/ENG_WI_T1_08-10JAN1935_MR Cricinfo], with a fuller version in ''The Illustrated History of the Test Match'' by Peter Arnold and Peter Wynne-Thomas, 1988
#{{note|1939 tour}} See [https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Seasons/ENG/1939_ENG_West_Indies_in_England_1939.html CricketArchive] and [http://www.cricinfo.com/link_to_database/ARCHIVE/1930S/1939/WI_IN_ENG/ Cricinfo] for the first-class scorecards
#{{note|1947–48 tour}} See [https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Seasons/WI/1947-48_WI_Marylebone_Cricket_Club_in_West_Indies_1947-48.html CricketArchive] and [http://www.cricinfo.com/link_to_database/ARCHIVE/1940S/1947-48/ENG_IN_WI/ Cricinfo] for the first-class scorecards
#{{note|Ganteaume record}} See [[List of Test cricket records]]. Ganteaume remains the player with the highest Test match career average (see [http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/westindies/content/player/51874.html Cricinfo])
#{{note|Indian independence}} Pakistan became independent on 14 August 1947, and India became independent one day later.
#{{note|1948 Pakistan tour}} See [https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Seasons/PAK/1948-49_PAK_West_Indies_in_Pakistan_1948-49.html CricketArchive] or [http://www.cricinfo.com/link_to_database/ARCHIVE/1940S/1948-49/WI_IN_PAK/ Cricinfo] for the first-class scorecards.
#{{note|1948 Ceylon tour}} See [https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Seasons/SL/1948-49_SL_West_Indies_in_Ceylon_1948-49.html CricketArchive] or [http://www.cricinfo.com/link_to_database/ARCHIVE/1940S/1948-49/WI_IN_CEYLON/ Cricinfo] for the first-class scorecards.
#{{note|1948 Indian tour}} See [https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Seasons/IND/1948-49_IND_West_Indies_in_India_1948-49.html CricketArchive] or [http://www.cricinfo.com/link_to_database/ARCHIVE/1940S/1948-49/WI_IN_IND/ Cricinfo] for the first-class scorecards.
#{{note|Ramadhin and Valentine}} The West Indies secured their first ever victory against England in the Second Test at Lord's. The match was won by 326 runs, with Ramadhin and Valentine taking 18 of the 20 wickets. The event was immortalised by the composition of a song, ''[[Victory Calypso]]''. The last two lines have gone down in cricketing folklore. The words are: Cricket lovely Cricket, // At Lord's where I saw it; // Cricket lovely Cricket, // At Lord's where I saw it; // Yardley tried his best // But Goddard won the Test. // They gave the crowd plenty fun; // Second Test and West Indies won. // With those two little pals of mine // Ramadhin and Valentine.
#{{note|1950 tour}} See [https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Seasons/ENG/1950_ENG_West_Indies_in_England_1950.html CricketArchive] or [http://www.cricinfo.com/link_to_database/ARCHIVE/1950S/1950/WI_IN_ENG/ Cricinfo] for the first-class scorecards.
#{{note|1951–52 Australia tour}} See [https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Seasons/AUS/1951-52_AUS_West_Indies_in_Australia_1951-52.html CricketArchive] or [http://www.cricinfo.com/link_to_database/ARCHIVE/1950S/1951-52/WI_IN_AUS/ Cricinfo] for the first-class scorecards.
#{{note|1951–52 New Zealand tour}} See [https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Seasons/NZ/1951-52_NZ_West_Indies_in_New_Zealand_1951-52.html CricketArchive] or [http://www.cricinfo.com/link_to_database/ARCHIVE/1950S/1951-52/WI_IN_NZ/ Cricinfo] for the first-class scorecards.
#{{note|1953 tour}} See [https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Seasons/WI/1952-53_WI_India_in_West_Indies_1952-53.html CricketArchive] or [http://www.cricinfo.com/link_to_database/ARCHIVE/1950S/1952-53/IND_IN_WI/ Cricinfo] for the first-class scorecards.
#{{note|1954–55 tour}} See [https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Seasons/WI/1953-54_WI_Marylebone_Cricket_Club_in_West_Indies_1953-54.html CricketArchive] or [http://www.cricinfo.com/link_to_database/ARCHIVE/1950S/1953-54/ENG_IN_WI/ Cricinfo] for the first-class scorecards.
#{{note|1955–56 tour}} See [https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Seasons/NZ/1955-56_NZ_West_Indies_in_New_Zealand_1955-56.html CricketArchive] or [http://www.cricinfo.com/link_to_database/ARCHIVE/1950S/1955-56/WI_IN_NZ/ Cricinfo] for the first-class scorecards.
#{{note|First NZ win}} New Zealand gained Test status at the same times as the West Indies and India. It took them 45 games since gaining Test status in 1926 to record their first win. Both figures are world records.
#{{note|1957 tour}} See [https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Seasons/ENG/1957_ENG_West_Indies_in_England_1957.html CricketArchive] or [http://www.cricinfo.com/link_to_database/ARCHIVE/1950S/1957/WI_IN_ENG/ Cricinfo] for the first-class scorecards.
#{{note|1957–58 tour}} See [https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Seasons/WI/1957-58_WI_Pakistan_in_West_Indies_1957-58.html CricketArchive] or [http://www.cricinfo.com/link_to_database/ARCHIVE/1950S/1957-58/PAK_IN_WI/ Cricinfo] for the first-class scorecards.
#{{note|Sobers 365}} [[Gary Sobers]]' 365 not out of a total of 790 for 3 declared was made in 614 minutes. It included 38 [[boundary (cricket)|fours]]. At the time it was a world record score, beating the 364 made by [[Len Hutton]] for [[English cricket team|England]] against [[Australian cricket team|Australia]] in 1938. It was finally beaten by fellow West Indian [[Brian Lara]]'s 375 against England in 1993–94. In the same innings [[Conrad Hunte]] made 260 before being [[run out]]. The West Indies won the game on the sixth day by an innings and 174 runs. See [https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/22/22847.html CricketArchive] for the scorecard. See also: [[List of Test cricket records]].
#{{note|1958–59 India tour}} See [https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Seasons/IND/1958-59_IND_West_Indies_in_India_1958-59.html CricketArchive] or [http://www.cricinfo.com/link_to_database/ARCHIVE/1950S/1958-59/WI_IN_IND/ Cricinfo] for the first-class scorecards.
#{{note|1958–59 Pakistan tour}} See [https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Seasons/PAK/1958-59_PAK_West_Indies_in_Pakistan_1958-59.html CricketArchive] or [http://www.cricinfo.com/link_to_database/ARCHIVE/1950S/1958-59/WI_IN_PAK/ Cricinfo] for the first-class scorecards.
#{{note|1959–60 tour}} See [https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Seasons/WI/1959-60_WI_Marylebone_Cricket_Club_in_West_Indies_1959-60.html CricketArchive] or [http://www.cricinfo.com/link_to_database/ARCHIVE/1950S/1959-60/ENG_IN_WI/ Cricinfo] for the first-class scorecards.
#{{note|Calls for black captain}} For CLR James's support of Worrell as captain see, for example, the summary on pp11, 135 of ''Cricket and Race'' by Jack Williams {{ISBN|1-85973-309-3}}. For Constantine's support for a black captain see pp37, 49 of the same book. Worrell was the first black to captain the West Indies for a whole series.
#{{note|Early black captains}} p38 of ''Cricket and Race'' by Jack Williams {{ISBN|1-85973-309-3}}
#{{note|Worrell captain}} See, for example, p135 of ''Cricket and Race'' by Jack Williams {{ISBN|1-85973-309-3}}
#{{note|Best team}} As noted above, there was no official World Test championship, so there are no generally agreed start and end dates of West Indian dominance. It is generally accepted that the Windies came to the fore in the mid-to-late 1960s.
#{{note|1960 Australia}} For a description of this tour see, for example,  [https://web.archive.org/web/20051123210505/http://abc.net.au/calypso/history.htm ABC's Calypso Summer website describing the 1960–61 Australian tour]. See [https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Seasons/AUS/1960-61_AUS_West_Indies_in_Australia_1960-61.html CricketArchive] or [http://www.cricinfo.com/link_to_database/ARCHIVE/1960S/1960-61/WI_IN_AUS/ Cricinfo] for the scorecards.
#{{note|Best series}} There is, of course, no official designation of what the greatest Test series ever is. However, this appellation has most notably been used for the 1960–61 Australia v West Indies series (see [https://web.archive.org/web/20051123210505/http://abc.net.au/calypso/history.htm ABC's Calypso Summer website describing the 1960–61 Australian tour], for example) and for [[the 2005 Ashes]] (see, for example, ''Ashes Victory The Official Story of the Greatest Ever Test Series in the Team's Own Words'' by The England Cricket Team {{ISBN|0-7528-7517-5}}). Similar claims have also been made for a small number of other series.
#{{note|World record crowd}} The record was achieved on 11 February 1961 (see [https://web.archive.org/web/20050630190405/http://www.mcg.org.au/content/document/00000079-src.pdf MCG's highest attendances for cricket (pdf)]
#{{note|1960–61 reaction}} See, for example, [https://web.archive.org/web/20051123210505/http://abc.net.au/calypso/history.htm ABC's Calypso Summer website describing the 1960–61 Australian tour]
#{{note|India 1961–62}} See [https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Seasons/WI/1961-62_WI_India_in_West_Indies_1961-62.html CricketArchive] or [http://www.cricinfo.com/link_to_database/ARCHIVE/1960S/1961-62/IND_IN_WI/ Cricinfo] for the first-class scorecards.
#{{note|1963 tour}} See [https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Seasons/ENG/1963_ENG_West_Indies_in_England_1963.html CricketArchive] or [http://www.cricinfo.com/link_to_database/ARCHIVE/1960S/1963/WI_IN_ENG/ Cricinfo] for the first-class scorecards.
#{{note|Cowdrey broken arm}} See Cowdrey's [http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/player/10846.html Cricinfo] page. For the scorecard, see [https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/26/26175.html CricketArchive].
