{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2017}}
{{Use British English|date=August 2017}}
[[File:Automobile Palace, Llandrindod 02.JPG|thumb|right|National Cycle Collection]]
The '''National Cycle Collection''' of Wales is a collection of bicycles through the ages established in 1997, and located in [[Llandrindod Wells]], [[Wales]], [[United Kingdom]].  It contains around 250 bicycles from 1818 to 2005, including a large collection of penny farthings and solid tyred safety bicycles, as well as cycling books, accessories and paraphernalia.<ref name=bbcpix>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-19585315 |title=In pictures: National Cycle Museum in Wales |website=''BBC News'' |date=14 September 2012 |accessdate=2017-08-31 }}</ref>

The building and site was known as The Automobile Palace, a project of bicycle shop owner Tom Norton who bought the site in 1906 for his expanding business.<ref name=motorsport>{{cite web|url=http://www.motorsportmagazine.com/archive/article/july-1963/57/pioneer-welsh-motor-business |title=A pioneer Welsh motor business |website=Motorsport Magazine |date=July 1963 |accessdate=2017-08-31 }}</ref> The building was initially completed in 1911 in an [[Art Deco]] style and then tripled in size, to the same standard, in 1919. It has received a Grade II* [[Listed building|heritage listing]], being "an exceptionally early grid-pattern steel-framed building surviving largely unaltered".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britishlistedbuildings.co.uk/300009064-the-automobile-palace-llandrindod-wells |title=The Automobile Palace |website=British Listed Buildings |accessdate=2017-08-31 }}</ref>

